Personal Moderators of Emotional Processing

Author

Taya Hoy

Research Problem and Objective

Despite extensive research regarding the personal construction of emotion and sensation, specific personal moderators of perception, such as personality, sensitivity to stimuli, personal history, and orientation to one’s physical body, have not been sufficiently evaluated. An experimental approach was undertaken to investigate relationships between such moderators and baseline affective and somatic sensations, and to evaluate the predictive power of personal moderators above and beyond the impact of affective stimuli.

Methods

Participants (N = 85) were asked to complete questionnaires relating to defined personal moderators, and randomly assigned to view positive or negative affective stimuli via 56 images, before completing questionnaires relating to interoceptive awareness, affective valence, and somatic sensation.

Results

Various personal moderators were significantly associated with baseline sensation and affect, including:

  • adverse childhood experiences (ACEs), (b = 0.10, SE = 0.05, p = .05);

  • extraversion, (β = 10.67, p = .02, η² = .07);

  • low sensory threshold, (b = 0.22, SE = 0.09, p = .02);

  • Noticing, (b = 0.84, SE = 0.27, p = .002);

  • Attention Regulation, (b = -0.73, SE = 0.27, p = .006); and

  • Body Trusting, (β = 25.53, p = .008, η² = .09).

Following the intervention,

  • extraversion, (β = 10.79, p = .02, η² = .03) and Attention Regulation, (β = -15.29, p = .03, η² = .06) predicted affective arousal;

  • Body Listening, (β = -31.82, p = .01, η² = .09) predicted affective valence;

  • ACEs, (b = 0.13, SE = 0.23, p = .02), Noticing, (b = 0.78, SE = 0.29, p = .007), and Attention Regulation, (b = -0.70, SE = 0.29, p = .02) predicted unpleasant sensation; and

  • low sensory threshold, (b = 0.23, SE = 0.09, p = .009), Body Trusting, (b = 0.38, SE = 0.18, p = .04), and Self-Regulation, (b = -0.49, SE = 0.20, p = .01) predicted pleasant sensation.

Finally, participants who underwent abstraction priming prior to viewing affective images demonstrated greater Attention Regulation, (χ2 = 6.11, p = .01, η² = .06) and Body Listening, (F = 5.87, p = .02, η² = .07).

Exploratory analyses revealed significant positive relationships between:

  • masculine gender identity and Not Worrying, (F = 4.39, p = .02, η² = .09);

  • feminine gender identity and neuroticism, (F = 8.86, p = .003), ease of excitation, (F = 3.74, p = .03, η² = 0.08), and low sensory threshold, (F = 8.99, p = .0003, η² = 0.18);

  • Major Depressive Disorder and neuroticism, (t = -3.12, p = .005, d = -0.84), ease of excitation, (t = -2.10, p = .05, d = -0.62), and low sensory threshold, (t = -2.47, p = .02, d = -0.73);

  • Generalized Anxiety Disorder and neuroticism, (t = -5.30, p < .001, d = -1.32), ease of excitation, (t = 2.47, p = .02, d = 0.61), and low sensory threshold, (t = 2.73, p = .01, d = 0.70);

  • Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder and Noticing,(t = 3.32, p = .006, d = 0.92), and ACEs, (t = 2.89, p = .02, d = 1.11);

as well as negative relationships between:

  • Major Depressive Disorder and Self-Regulation, (t = 2.63, p = .01, d = 0.72), Body Listening, (t = 2.42, p = .02, d = 0.67), Body Trusting, (t = 3.37, p = .003, d = 1.06), and extraversion, (t = 3.12, p = .004, d = 0.79);

  • Generalized Anxiety Disorder and Body Trusting, (t = 2.06, p = .05, d = 0.57), and conscientiousness, (t = 2.56, p = .02, d = 0.67); and

  • Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder and agreeableness, (t = -3.06, p = .01, d = -1.15).

Conclusion

This study suggests the presence of small to moderate relationships between various personal moderators and affective and somatic sensation. Further, abstraction priming had an unexpectedly positive impact on interoceptive awareness. More research is needed to evaluate the impact of personal moderators on sensation and affect in the context of physiological stress and mindfulness-based interventions.

Research Questions:

  1. Are baseline sensations associated with personal moderators such as ACEs, neuroticism, sensory processing sensitivity (SPS), and interoceptive awareness (IA)?

  2. Are reactive sensations to affective content (positive or negative) associated with personal moderators?

  3. Is interoceptive awareness influenced by embodiment versus abstraction priming?

Hypotheses:

ACEs: Positive correlations are expected between ACEs and unpleasant somatic sensations, high-arousal negative affect (HNA), and low-arousal negative affect (LNA), and negative correlations between ACEs and pleasant sensations and positive affect (PA).

Neuroticism: Neuroticism is expected to positively correlate with unpleasant sensations, HNA, and LNA, and negatively with pleasant sensations and PA.

IA: IA is expected to negatively correlate with unpleasant sensations, HNA, and LNA, and positively with pleasant sensations and PA.

SPS: SPS is expected to influence both unpleasant and pleasant sensations, HNA, LNA, and PA.

ACEs and Affective Content: ACE scores will predict greater unpleasant sensations, HNA, and LNA, and fewer pleasant sensations and lower PA following exposure to negative affective content.

Neuroticism and Affective Content: Neuroticism will predict more unpleasant sensations, greater HNA and LNA, fewer pleasant sensations, and lower PA following exposure to negative affective content.

SPS and Affective Content: SPS may predict more unpleasant sensations, fewer pleasant sensations, greater HNA and LNA, and lower PA following exposure to negative affective content, while positive content will likely increase pleasant sensations and PA for HSPs.

IA and Affective Content: IA is expected to follow a similar pattern, with negative content predicting more unpleasant sensations, fewer pleasant sensations, greater HNA and LNA, and lower PA, and positive content predicting more pleasant sensations, fewer unpleasant sensations, greater PA, and lower HNA and LNA.

Priming Effects: Embodiment priming is expected to alter the relationship between personal factors and affective/somatic sensations, with changes in IA pre- and post-priming, while no such change is expected under abstraction priming.

P_Valence <- (P_HA_PV + P_LA_PV) - (P_HA_NV + P_LA_NV)
culmination <- cbind(culmination, P_Valence)

#clean up post-experiment somatic sensation 
P_SV <- subset(dataframe, select = c(SM_POST_1:SM_POST_787))
P_SV <- P_SV %>%
  mutate(across(SM_POST_1:SM_POST_787, ~dplyr::recode(., "Dislike" = -1, "Neutral" = 0, "Like" = 1)))

#define post-experiment somatic sensation
P_US <- colSums(apply(P_SV, 1, grepl, pattern = "-1"))
culmination <- cbind(culmination, P_US)

P_PS <- colSums(apply(P_SV, 1, grepl, pattern = "1"))
culmination <- cbind(culmination, P_PS)

P_Ratio <- P_US / P_PS
culmination <- cbind(culmination, P_Ratio)

Emotional Affect at Baseline

The Brief Mood Introspection Scale - Visual Analog (BMIS-VA) is scored by subtracting the aggregate positive valence score by the aggregate negative valence score. Scores above zero indicate overall positive affect, while scores below zero indicate overall negative affect. Similarly, affective arousal is measured by subtracting the aggregate high arousal score from the aggregate low arousal score, with negative values indicating a predominance of low arousal and values above zero indicating a predominance of high arousal.

At baseline, the average valence score was 59.74 (SD = 56.57) and the average arousal score was -34.89 (SD = 23.17).

Somatic Valence and Well-Being at Baseline

The Sensation Manikin (SM) measures valenced sensations throughout the body using 786 sensation pixels. The sensation ratio demonstrates predominance of sensation valence, with values larger than 1 indicating a greater prevalence of unpleasant sensation, values less than 1 indicating a greater prevalence of pleasant sensation, and 1 indicating equal parts pleasant and unpleasant.

At baseline, participants reported, on average, 15.65 (SD = 18.52) unpleasant sensations and 29.54 (SD = 30.15) pleasant sensations. The average sensation ratio score was 0.58 (SD = .37).

Show the code 
Base_Somatic <- data.frame(
  Unpleasant = US,
  Pleasant = PS,
  Ratio = Ratio

Psychometric Properties

MAIA-2

The internal consistency of the MAIA-2 in the current study was excellent, with a Cronbach’s Alpha of .91 at both administration times.

BFI-2-XS

The internal consistency of the BFI-2-XS in the current study was unacceptable, with an alpha of .48.

HSPS

The internal consistency of the HSPS in the current study was acceptable, with an alpha of .73.

ACE-10

The internal consistency of the ACE-10 in the current study was acceptable, with an alpha of .80.

BMIS-VA

The internal consistency of the BMIS-VA in the current study was acceptable, with an alpha of .73 at both administration times.

SM

The internal consistency of the SM in the current study was excellent, with an alpha of .97 at baseline and .98 at post-intervention.

The relationships between personal moderators and baseline affect, personal moderators on post-intervention affect after accounting for experimental conditions, and the impact of the priming condition on interoceptive awareness will be evaluated using linear regression, assuming hypothesis testing assumptions are reasonably well-met.

Count Data Assumptions

Given the usage of count data to measure pleasant and unpleasant sensation, multiple linear regression is not appropriate.

Baseline Unpleasant Sensation
Show the code 
PRE_US.glm <- glm(formula = US ~ O + C + E + A + N + EOE + LST + AES + ACE + No + ND + NW + AR + EA + SR + BL + BT, family = "poisson", data = personal_moderators)

dispersiontest(PRE_US.glm)

    Overdispersion test

data:  PRE_US.glm
z = 5.7532, p-value = 0.000000004379
alternative hypothesis: true dispersion is greater than 1
sample estimates:
dispersion 
  9.921921

As the dispersion estimate is larger than 1, the model is too overdispersed to conduct a Poisson regression. Therefore, a negative binomial regression may be more appropriate. It’s necessary to first test multichollinearity.

Personal Moderators and Somatic Processing

Unpleasant Sensation

The affective content has a significant impact on reported unpleasant sensations, (p = 4.93e-05), while the priming condition does not, (p = .63). As far as personal moderators impact the model, for every additional ACE reported, the expected number of US in response to the stimuli increases by 0.12 (p = .02). Further, for every unit-increase in Noticing and Attention Regulation, the expected number of reported US increases by 0.78 (p = .007) and decreases by 0.70 (p = .02), respectively.
